response:
The area of the triangle is half the area of the parallelogram, so we can find the area of the parallelogram and divide by 2. The area of the parallelogram is the magnitude of the cross product of the vectors $\overrightarrow{OA}$ and $\overrightarrow{OB}.$

\begin{align*} \overrightarrow{OA} \times \overrightarrow{OB} &= \begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\ 1 & 2 & 3 \\ -3 & -2 & 1 \end{vmatrix} \\ &= \mathbf{i} \begin{vmatrix} 2 & 3 \\ -2 & 1 \end{vmatrix} - \mathbf{j} \begin{vmatrix} 1 & 3 \\ -3 & 1 \end{vmatrix} + \mathbf{k} \begin{vmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ -3 & -2 \end{vmatrix} \\ &= \mathbf{i} (2 + 6) - \mathbf{j} (1 + 9) + \mathbf{k} (-2 + 6) \\ &= \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ -10 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}

The magnitude of this vector is $\sqrt{8^2 + (-10)^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{164} = 2 \sqrt{41}.$ Therefore, the area of the parallelogram is $2 \sqrt{41},$ so the area of the triangle is $\boxed{\sqrt{41}}.$

